@Reasoning
Extracts the second source register_id from an LIRInstruction's third
operand slot (offset 24). Required for binary-operation lowering, where
the optimizer must inspect both source registers (src1 + src2) to decide
between two-address and three-address encodings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the instruction pointer; return 0 on NULL.
2. Load the second-source-operand pointer at instruction offset 24.
3. NULL-guard the operand; return 0 on NULL.
4. Read operand_type at LIROperand offset 0; if it is not
   OPERAND_TYPE_REGISTER, return 0. This rejects immediate and memory
   operands whose register_id slot is undefined.
5. Return register_id at LIROperand offset 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two memory loads plus one compare-and-branch (the type guard). Inlinable.
Total cost matches the legacy inline-offset reads being centralized, so
no regression from the consolidation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe at both the instruction layer and the operand layer. Returning
0 for non-register operands ensures optimizer dead-code detection cannot
be fooled by an immediate value whose low byte happens to match a
register encoding.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_src2_reg" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let src2_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 24
    If src2_operand is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let operand_type be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src2_operand, 0
    If operand_type is not equal to OPERAND_TYPE_REGISTER:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src2_operand, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Extracts the immediate value carried by an LIRInstruction, regardless
of which operand slot holds it. The LIR constructors place immediates
in different slots depending on instruction shape: LOAD_IMM carries the
constant in the src1 slot, LOAD/STORE carry the displacement in the
slot not occupied by their register operands, and fused compare-branch
forms carry the target in whichever slot remains after both source
registers. Backends that lower by opcode (mips, powerpc) need a single
slot-agnostic read; this accessor provides the uniform operand-walker
contract that create_lir_jump's design notes promise: any analysis can
read an instruction's immediate the same way for every instruction
kind.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the instruction pointer; return 0 on NULL.
2. Walk the operand slots in source order (src1 at offset 16, src2 at
   offset 24, dest at offset 8). Source slots are checked first because
   immediates that parameterize an operation (constants, displacements,
   targets) are inputs, and the dest slot is checked last so a
   destination immediate (store displacement forms) is still found.
3. For each non-NULL operand whose operand_type at offset 0 equals
   OPERAND_TYPE_IMMEDIATE, return its immediate_value at offset 16.
4. Return 0 when no operand slot holds an immediate.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
At most six loads and three compares; typically two loads when the
immediate sits in src1. Inlinable. No allocation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe at both the instruction and operand layers. Type
discrimination via OPERAND_TYPE_IMMEDIATE guarantees the value read at
offset 16 is the immediate_value field and never a register id or
memory descriptor reinterpreted as a constant.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_immediate" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let src1_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 16
    If src1_operand is not equal to 0:
        Let src1_type be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src1_operand, 0
        If src1_type is equal to OPERAND_TYPE_IMMEDIATE:
            Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src1_operand, 16
        End If
    End If
    Let src2_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 24
    If src2_operand is not equal to 0:
        Let src2_type be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src2_operand, 0
        If src2_type is equal to OPERAND_TYPE_IMMEDIATE:
            Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src2_operand, 16
        End If
    End If
    Let dest_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 8
    If dest_operand is not equal to 0:
        Let dest_type be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dest_operand, 0
        If dest_type is equal to OPERAND_TYPE_IMMEDIATE:
            Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dest_operand, 16
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Extracts the branch-target label id from a jump or compare-and-branch
LIRInstruction. Per the operand-walker contract established by
create_lir_jump, control-flow targets are wrapped as immediate operands
(the label id sits in the immediate_value slot), so retrieving a branch
target is the slot-agnostic immediate read. A dedicated accessor exists
alongside get_immediate because the two reads answer different
questions at call sites — "what constant does this ALU op use" versus
"where does control go" — and backends (mips, powerpc) lower the two
cases through different emitters. Keeping the names distinct preserves
that intent even though the retrieval mechanics coincide today; if
label operands ever gain a dedicated operand_type, only this accessor
changes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Delegate to get_immediate, which walks src1/src2/dest and returns
   the immediate_value of the first immediate-class operand.
2. The returned value is the target block/label id used by the
   backend's .LBB label emission; 0 means the instruction carries no
   target (malformed or register-indirect control flow).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Cost identical to get_immediate plus one call frame; inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe via get_immediate. The label id is consumed only for label
name construction, never dereferenced, so a 0 sentinel cannot cause a
wild pointer access in callers that respect the 0-means-absent
contract.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_branch_target" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get_immediate with instruction
End Process

@Reasoning
Extracts the direct call target from an LIR_CALL instruction. The call
constructors wrap the callee's function-name string pointer as an
immediate operand in the src1 slot, mirroring how jumps wrap their
label ids; indirect calls instead place a register operand there and
must be detected by the backend before calling this accessor (a 0
return distinguishes the indirect/absent case). A dedicated accessor
keeps the pointer-valued read (function name string) nominally separate
from the integer-valued reads (constants, label ids) at backend call
sites.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Delegate to get_immediate; for direct calls the first immediate
   operand's value slot holds the function-name string pointer.
2. Return 0 for indirect calls (register operand in src1) or malformed
   instructions, signaling the backend to take its indirect path.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Cost identical to get_immediate plus one call frame; inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe via get_immediate. The returned value is a pointer to a
NUL-terminated function name owned by the LIR module; callers must
treat 0 as absent and must not free the string, which the module
arena owns.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_call_target" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get_immediate with instruction
End Process

@Reasoning
Writes the encoding-variant identifier into the base LIRInstruction's
metadata slot at offset 56. The metadata slot is reserved by
create_lir_instruction precisely for this kind of per-instruction
backend hint and is zero-initialized so a "no encoding decision yet"
value is unambiguous.

Encoding variants are an x86-64-flavored property: most arithmetic,
logic, move, and compare opcodes have multiple binary encodings the
backend must pick between (short 1-2 byte form, long 3+ byte form, or
a register-specific optimized form such as the RAX-targeted accumulator
encoding). Instruction selection runs the heuristic in
instruction_select.select_instruction_encoding once per instruction;
storing the result here lets the emitter consume the decision without
re-running the heuristic, and keeps the encoding choice visible to
peephole and diagnostics passes that inspect instructions.

The accessor is base-instruction-shaped: callers pass the same pointer
they would pass to get_opcode / get_dest_reg. Specialized wrappers
(LIRBinaryOp, LIRMove, etc.) carry their base pointer at offset 0, so
callers holding a wrapper must extract the base first via offset 0.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the instruction pointer so the accessor is safe to call
   on partially constructed LIR.
2. Write the encoding value into the metadata slot at offset 56 via the
   standard memory_set_int64 primitive.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Single memory store with one branch (the NULL guard). Inlinable.
Called at most once per instruction during instruction selection, so
the cost is dwarfed by the surrounding selection heuristic.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe at the instruction pointer. The encoding value itself is a
plain integer identifier (0=short, 1=long, 2=RAX-optimized in the
current x86-64 heuristic) and requires no sanitization. Writing into
the metadata slot does not alias any operand or linkage field of the
base LIRInstruction layout.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "set_instruction_encoding" that takes instruction as Integer, encoding as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 56, encoding
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Reads the encoding-variant identifier previously written into the base
LIRInstruction's metadata slot by set_instruction_encoding. The return
value matches the contract of
instruction_select.select_instruction_encoding: 0 = short form,
1 = long form, 2 = register-specific optimized form. A return value of
0 is also produced for instructions that have not been visited by
instruction selection, because create_lir_instruction zero-initializes
the metadata slot — callers that need to distinguish "no decision yet"
from "short form chosen" must track that out-of-band.

Accessor symmetry with set_instruction_encoding keeps the offset
constant in exactly one place; future extensions (e.g. widening the
metadata slot to a packed bitfield encoding additional hints) require
a single edit here rather than touching every reader.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the instruction pointer; return 0 on NULL so dead-code
   detection and emitter fallback paths can default to the short
   encoding.
2. Read the metadata slot at offset 56 and return it.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Single memory load with one branch (the NULL guard). Inlinable.
Called at most once per instruction during emission.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe. The slot contents are a plain integer; no pointer
dereference and no sanitization needed.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_instruction_encoding" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 56
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR INSTRUCTION CREATION FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Constructs the base 72-byte LIRInstruction record shared by every
specialized instruction kind (move, binary, unary, compare, load, store,
call, return, branch, jump, label, nop). Specialized constructors layer
a kind-specific record on top and call back here for the common fields;
centralizing the layout here means a future extension (e.g. an extra
metadata slot) requires a single edit instead of touching every
constructor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate a fixed 72-byte block via Layout.allocate.
2. Emit a diagnostic and return 0 on allocation failure so callers can
   propagate the OOM condition.
3. Write the supplied opcode into the opcode slot at offset 0.
4. Zero the remaining eight 8-byte slots (result, operand1, operand2,
   operand3, next, parent_block, metadata, instruction_index). Zero-
   initialization is required because downstream passes interpret 0 as
   "no operand / no link / no metadata".
5. Return the instruction pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One 72-byte allocation plus nine stores; the only branch is the OOM
guard. Inlinable by the LIR optimizer. Called for every instruction
constructed in the program, so the linear store pattern matters for
hot-path locality.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Allocation failure is surfaced as a 0 return so specialized constructors
can avoid wrapping a NULL base. Zero-initialization of every operand
slot prevents leakage of stale allocator memory into instruction
fields that downstream code treats as pointers.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_instruction" that takes opcode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Sep-comp port: instruction record extended from 72 to 80 bytes to carry the
    Note: @PLT cross-object flag at offset 72 (set on LIR_CALL by lower_call from the
    Note: MIR call's cross_module flag; read by emit_call to choose `callq <sym>@PLT`
    Note: vs `callq <sym>`). Default 0 for every instruction shape.
    Let instruction be proc allocate from Layout with 80
    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Display "create_lir_instruction: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 0, opcode
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 8, 0   Note: result
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 16, 0  Note: operand1
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 24, 0  Note: operand2
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 32, 0  Note: operand3
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 40, 0  Note: next
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 48, 0  Note: parent_block
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 56, 0  Note: metadata
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 64, 0  Note: instruction_index
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 72, 0  Note: sep-comp @PLT cross-module flag

    Return instruction
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs a move instruction — the most common LIR operation, used for
register-to-register transfers, immediate-to-register loads, memory
loads (memory → register), and stores (register → memory). The single
LIRMove record covers all variants because the backend distinguishes
them by operand kinds at emission time rather than by separate opcodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate a 48-byte LIRMove block via Layout.allocate.
2. On allocation failure, emit a diagnostic and return 0.
3. Construct the underlying LIRInstruction base with LIR_MOV opcode.
4. If base construction failed, deallocate the move block and return 0
   so no half-initialized instruction escapes.
5. Populate the LIRMove fields: base pointer (offset 0), destination
   (offset 8), source (offset 16), move_size (offset 24), and zero
   is_sign_extend and is_zero_extend (offsets 32 and 40) — extension
   semantics default to plain copy.
6. Mirror the destination and source operands into the base instruction's
   operand slots (offsets 8 and 16) so generic passes that walk
   LIRInstruction can read them without down-casting.
7. Return the move instruction pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two allocations (48-byte move + 72-byte base) plus a handful of stores.
The OOM-cleanup path runs a single deallocate. Inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Both allocations are NULL-checked. The intermediate failure path cleans
up the move allocation before returning 0 to prevent a leak; without
that cleanup a partial OOM would orphan the 48-byte block. No operand
fields are validated here — operand-kind compatibility (e.g. forbidding
memory-to-memory moves) is enforced by the LIR verifier.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_move" that takes destination as Integer, source as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: A LIR move is a single FLAT LIRInstruction: opcode at offset 0,
    Note: destination at 8 (the generic result slot), source at 16 (operand1).
    Note: The entire backend - instruction selection (reads opcode@0,
    Note: result@8, op1@16), register allocation, and the x86-64 asm emitter -
    Note: reads instructions at these flat offsets. The move therefore IS that
    Note: flat record; it must NOT be a separate wrapper carrying a base
    Note: pointer at offset 0, because the emitter reads offset 0 as the opcode
    Note: and would treat the base pointer as a (garbage) opcode value. size is
    Note: carried by the operand records, so no separate size slot is needed.
    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with LIR.LIR_MOV
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 8, destination
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 16, source

    Return base
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs a binary-operation instruction. Binary ops are
three-address-form abstractions (destination, left, right) over the
typical machine encodings: add, sub, mul, div, and, or, xor, shifts.
The destination operand is explicit even on two-address ISAs like
x86-64 because instruction selection re-materializes the form during
lowering, and many ops legitimately set CPU flags as a side effect.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate a 48-byte LIRBinaryOp block.
2. On allocation failure, emit a diagnostic and return 0.
3. Construct the base LIRInstruction with the supplied opcode.
4. On base failure, deallocate the binary-op block and return 0.
5. Populate base pointer, destination, left, right, operation_size, and
   sets_flags=1 — every supported binary op sets at least one flag on
   x86-64; passes that need to reason about flag clobbers consult this
   field rather than re-deriving per opcode.
6. Mirror destination, left, and right into the base instruction's
   operand slots so generic walkers can access them.
7. Return the binary-op pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two allocations (48-byte op + 72-byte base) plus ten stores. The
OOM-cleanup path runs a single deallocate. Inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe at both allocations; the intermediate failure path cleans up
the op block so no leak occurs. Operand-kind compatibility is the
verifier's responsibility, not this constructor's.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_binary_op" that takes opcode as Integer, destination as Integer, left as Integer, right as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Flat LIRInstruction: opcode@0, destination@8 (result slot), left@16
    Note: (operand1), right@24 (operand2) - the offsets instruction selection,
    Note: register allocation, and the asm emitter all read. Offset 0 must hold
    Note: the opcode itself, never a base pointer.
    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with opcode
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 8, destination
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 16, left
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 24, right

    Return base
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs a unary-operation instruction. Unary ops include negation,
bitwise NOT, increment, decrement, and sign-extension. The
three-address abstraction (separate destination and operand) lets a
single LIR form lower to either an in-place x86-64 encoding (`neg
%rax`) or to a multi-instruction sequence on RISC targets that lack a
direct unary form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate a 40-byte LIRUnaryOp block.
2. On allocation failure, emit a diagnostic and return 0.
3. Construct the base LIRInstruction with the supplied opcode.
4. On base failure, deallocate the unary-op block and return 0.
5. Populate base pointer, destination, operand, operation_size, and
   sets_flags=1.
6. Mirror destination and operand into the base instruction's operand
   slots.
7. Return the unary-op pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two allocations (40-byte op + 72-byte base) plus eight stores.
Inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe with leak-free OOM cleanup. Operand-kind compatibility is
checked by the verifier.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_unary_op" that takes opcode as Integer, destination as Integer, operand as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Flat LIRInstruction: opcode@0, destination@8 (result slot), operand@16
    Note: (operand1) - the offsets every backend pass reads. Offset 0 carries
    Note: the opcode, not a base pointer.
    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with opcode
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 8, destination
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 16, operand

    Return base
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs a compare instruction. Compares are flag-only operations:
they take two operands and set CPU flags without producing a value
result. A subsequent conditional branch consumes the flags. The
is_signed bit selects between signed and unsigned comparison semantics,
which affects flag interpretation (carry flag for unsigned, sign+
overflow for signed).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate a 40-byte LIRCompare block.
2. On allocation failure, emit a diagnostic and return 0.
3. Construct the base LIRInstruction with LIR_CMP opcode.
4. On base failure, deallocate the compare block and return 0.
5. Populate base pointer, left operand, right operand, compare_size,
   and is_signed.
6. Mirror left and right into the base instruction's operand slots
   (operand1 and operand2). Note that compares do not write a
   destination operand — the destination slot stays 0.
7. Return the compare pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two allocations (40-byte compare + 72-byte base) plus seven stores.
Inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe with leak-free OOM cleanup. The signedness flag is stored
verbatim; encoders interpret 0 as unsigned and non-zero as signed.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_compare" that takes left as Integer, right as Integer, size as Integer, is_signed as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Flat LIRInstruction: opcode@0, no result (a compare writes only CPU
    Note: flags, so the result slot at 8 stays 0), left@16 (operand1), right@24
    Note: (operand2) - matching the operand offsets the asm emitter and
    Note: instruction selection read. Offset 0 holds the opcode itself.
    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with LIR.LIR_CMP
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 16, left
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 24, right

    Return base
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs a memory-load instruction. Loads transfer data from memory
into a register destination. The dedicated LIRLoad record (versus a
generic move-with-memory-source) lets analyses distinguish memory
dependencies from register transfers and preserves alignment and
volatility information that the backend must honor on emission.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate a 56-byte LIRLoad block.
2. On allocation failure, emit a diagnostic and return 0.
3. Construct the base LIRInstruction with LIR_LOAD opcode.
4. On base failure, deallocate the load block and return 0.
5. Populate base pointer, destination operand, address operand,
   load_size, is_volatile=0, is_atomic=0, and alignment defaulting to
   the access size (natural alignment).
6. Mirror destination and address into the base instruction's operand
   slots.
7. Return the load pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two allocations (56-byte load + 72-byte base) plus nine stores.
Inlinable. Default volatility (0) lets later passes reorder the load
unless the caller explicitly upgrades the field afterwards.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe with leak-free OOM cleanup. Default alignment equals the
access size — this is the natural-alignment requirement of every
supported ISA, and any caller that needs over- or under-alignment must
overwrite the field. The address operand's effective-address validity
is the verifier's responsibility.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_load" that takes destination as Integer, address as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Flat LIRInstruction: opcode@0, destination@8 (result slot), address@16
    Note: (operand1) - the offsets the backend reads. Offset 0 holds the opcode,
    Note: not a base pointer. Volatility/alignment metadata is carried by the
    Note: address operand record.
    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with LIR.LIR_LOAD
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 8, destination
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 16, address

    Return base
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs a memory-store instruction. Stores write data from a
register or immediate source into memory. Like loads, stores carry
explicit alignment and volatility metadata that constrains downstream
reordering and instruction selection.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate a 56-byte LIRStore block.
2. On allocation failure, emit a diagnostic and return 0.
3. Construct the base LIRInstruction with LIR_STORE opcode.
4. On base failure, deallocate the store block and return 0.
5. Populate base pointer, address operand, source operand, store_size,
   is_volatile=0, is_atomic=0, and alignment defaulting to size.
6. Mirror address and source into the base instruction's operand slots
   1 and 2 (a store has no result destination — the destination slot at
   offset 8 stays 0).
7. Return the store pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two allocations (56-byte store + 72-byte base) plus nine stores.
Inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe with leak-free OOM cleanup. Default natural alignment
matches every supported ISA's minimum requirement.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_store" that takes address as Integer, source as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Flat LIRInstruction: opcode@0, no result (a store writes memory, not a
    Note: register, so the result slot at 8 stays 0), address@16 (operand1),
    Note: source@24 (operand2) - the offsets the backend reads. Offset 0 holds
    Note: the opcode itself.
    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with LIR.LIR_STORE
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 16, address
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 24, source

    Return base
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs a function-call instruction. Calls are the most complex LIR
instructions because they interact with calling conventions (argument
register assignment, stack alignment, caller-saved register
preservation, return-value placement). The LIRCall record carries
enough metadata for the backend to materialize the full prologue/
epilogue around the call site: the argument list (already lowered to
operands), the return register, an indirect flag for register callees,
a tail-call flag, and the calling-convention id.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate a 72-byte LIRCall block.
2. On allocation failure, emit a diagnostic and return 0.
3. Construct the base LIRInstruction with LIR_CALL opcode.
4. On base failure, deallocate the call block and return 0.
5. Populate base pointer, callee (function-name string id or register
   for indirect calls), arguments pointer (a list of operand
   pointers), arg_count, return_register, return_type=0 (filled in by
   the type-aware caller if known), is_indirect=0, is_tail_call=0, and
   calling_convention=0 (the platform default).
6. Return the call pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two allocations (72-byte call + 72-byte base) plus nine stores.
Inlinable. The argument list itself is not allocated here — the
caller passes a pre-built list pointer.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe with leak-free OOM cleanup. The arguments pointer is stored
verbatim; calling convention validation (number of register arguments,
stack layout) happens during instruction selection.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_call" that takes callee as Integer, arguments as Integer, arg_count as Integer, return_reg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    A LIR call is a single FLAT LIRInstruction, NOT a wrapper carrying a base
    pointer at offset 0. The entire backend reads instructions at flat offsets:
    instruction-selection and the x86-64 emitter read the opcode at offset 0,
    get_call_target/get_immediate read the callee through the src1 operand at
    offset 16, and emit_call reads the calling convention at offset 64. A prior
    wrapper layout stored the base LIRInstruction POINTER at offset 0, so the
    emitter read that pointer as the opcode (surfacing as
    "# unknown opcode: <pointer>") and never recognised the call — every call
    site emitted no callq. This mirrors the same flat-record discipline already
    documented on create_lir_move.

    The callee function-name string pointer is wrapped as an IMMEDIATE operand
    in the src1 slot (offset 16), matching the get_call_target contract ("the
    call constructors wrap the callee's function-name string pointer as an
    immediate operand in the src1 slot"). emit_call then reads
    src1_operand@16 -> value@16 to recover the name. Argument marshalling and
    the return-value move are emitted by lower_call as separate explicit LIR
    moves before/after this instruction, so the call record itself only needs
    the callee, return register (def for liveness), and calling convention.
    :End Note
    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with LIR.LIR_CALL
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Wrap the callee name pointer as an immediate operand in src1 (offset 16).
    If callee is not equal to 0:
        Let callee_operand be proc create_immediate_operand with callee, 8
        If callee_operand is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 16, callee_operand
    End If

    Note: calling_convention slot (offset 64). 0 = platform default (SysV/Win64);
    Note: lower_call overrides it for FFI externals. The dest slot (offset 8)
    Note: stays 0: the call result is delivered into the architectural return
    Note: register and copied out by an explicit move lower_call emits after the
    Note: call, so the call record carries no dest operand.
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 64, 0

    Return base
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs a return instruction. Returns transfer control out of the
current function and optionally carry a return value. A return record
does not need a specialized layout beyond the base LIRInstruction
because the only data it carries is the (optional) return-value
operand, which fits in the base's operand1 slot — the backend's
function-epilogue lowering picks up the rest of the return-handling
work (callee-saved restore, stack cleanup, ret instruction emission).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Construct the base LIRInstruction with LIR_RET opcode.
2. On base failure, propagate 0.
3. If a return-value operand was supplied (non-zero pointer), store it
   in the base instruction's operand1 slot at offset 16. A NULL return
   value leaves the slot at its default 0, which the epilogue
   interprets as "void return".
4. Return the base pointer directly.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One allocation (72-byte base) plus at most one store. Inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe on the base allocation. The return-value operand is stored
without further validation; an invalid operand pointer would be caught
by the verifier before code emission.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_return" that takes return_value as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with LIR.LIR_RET
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set return value operand if present
    If return_value is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 16, return_value
    End If

    Return base
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs a conditional-branch instruction. Branches check CPU flags
set by a preceding compare and transfer control to a target label
when the condition holds, falling through to the next block
otherwise. The condition code is one of CONDITION_EQ..CONDITION_UGE
(10 codes covering signed and unsigned compare semantics). The
branch_weight is a profile-derived hint (0–100, 50 = unknown) that
guides block-layout heuristics: a high weight encourages placing the
target on the fall-through side for better fetch locality.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate a 40-byte LIRBranch block.
2. On allocation failure, emit a diagnostic and return 0.
3. Construct the base LIRInstruction with LIR_BRANCH opcode.
4. On base failure, deallocate the branch block and return 0.
5. Populate base pointer, condition code, target_label, fall_through
   label, and branch_weight=50 (unknown profile, balanced layout).
6. Return the branch pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two allocations (40-byte branch + 72-byte base) plus six stores.
Inlinable. The 50-weight default lets layout passes recognize
unprofiled branches and skip aggressive reordering.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe with leak-free OOM cleanup. The condition code is stored
verbatim — the verifier enforces that it lies in the 0..9 range.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_branch" that takes condition as Integer, target_label as Integer, fall_through as Integer returns Integer:
    Let branch be proc allocate from Layout with 40
    If branch is equal to 0:
        Display "create_lir_branch: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with LIR.LIR_BRANCH
    If base is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with branch
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with branch, 0, base
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with branch, 8, condition
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with branch, 16, target_label
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with branch, 24, fall_through
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with branch, 32, 50  Note: branch_weight (50 = unknown)

    Return branch
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs an unconditional jump instruction. Jumps transfer control
to a fixed target label without consulting any condition. Encoded as
a base LIRInstruction with LIR_JMP opcode and the target label wrapped
as an 8-byte immediate operand in operand1. Wrapping the label in an
immediate keeps the generic operand-walker contract uniform across
every instruction kind — analyses that want the jump target read it
the same way they would read any other operand.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Construct the base LIRInstruction with LIR_JMP opcode.
2. On base failure, propagate 0.
3. Wrap the target_label as an 8-byte immediate operand via
   create_immediate_operand.
4. Store the immediate operand pointer in the base instruction's
   operand1 slot at offset 16.
5. Return the base pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One 72-byte base allocation plus one 64-byte immediate operand
allocation plus one store. The immediate is created unconditionally;
if the base allocation failed the immediate is not allocated either.
Inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe on the base allocation. The immediate-operand constructor
NULL-checks itself; if it returns 0, operand1 stays 0 and the verifier
flags the malformed jump.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_jump" that takes target_label as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with LIR.LIR_JMP
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Store target label in operand1
    Let label_operand be proc create_immediate_operand with target_label, 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 16, label_operand

    Return base
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs a label instruction. Labels mark positions in the
instruction stream that branches and jumps reference by id. They
produce no machine code themselves; the assembler emits a symbolic
label at the position. Storing both the numeric label_id (used for
intra-function references) and a label_name string id (used for
assembler output and debugging) keeps the IR self-describing without
forcing a name table lookup on every reference.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate a 24-byte LIRLabel block.
2. On allocation failure, emit a diagnostic and return 0.
3. Construct the base LIRInstruction with LIR_LABEL opcode.
4. On base failure, deallocate the label block and return 0.
5. Populate base pointer, label_id, and label_name.
6. Return the label pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two allocations (24-byte label + 72-byte base) plus three stores.
Inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe with leak-free OOM cleanup. The label_id and label_name are
stored verbatim; uniqueness of label_id within a function is the
caller's responsibility (the LIR builder enforces it via a counter).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_label" that takes label_id as Integer, label_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let label be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If label is equal to 0:
        Display "create_lir_label: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with LIR.LIR_LABEL
    If base is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with label
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with label, 0, base
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with label, 8, label_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with label, 16, label_name

    Return label
End Process

Process called "create_lir_inline_asm" that takes asm_text as Integer, dialect as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Build a LIR_INLINE_ASM instruction carrying verbatim target assembly text
    and the dialect flag (0=intel, 1=att).

    The backend's emit_inline_asm (asm_generator.runa:2187) reads
    operand1 = __load(instr, 16), then asm_text = __load(operand1, 16), and the
    dialect from the wrapper's offset 8. To satisfy those reads, this builds:
      - a standard LIRInstruction whose opcode (offset 0) is LIR_INLINE_ASM
        (30903), so the emit dispatcher routes it correctly;
      - a 24-byte text wrapper whose offset 8 holds the dialect flag and whose
        offset 16 holds the asm_text pointer;
      - the instruction's operand1 slot (offset 16) set to that wrapper.
    This mirrors the LIR_LABEL / LIR_COMMENT text-carrying convention the
    backend already expects.
    :End Note
    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with LIR.LIR_INLINE_ASM
    If base is equal to 0:
        Display "create_lir_inline_asm: base allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let wrapper be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If wrapper is equal to 0:
        Display "create_lir_inline_asm: wrapper allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with wrapper, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with wrapper, 8, dialect
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with wrapper, 16, asm_text

    Note: operand1 of the LIRInstruction (offset 16) points at the wrapper.
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 16, wrapper

    Return base
End Process

@Reasoning
Constructs a no-operation instruction. NOPs are emitted for alignment
padding (function entry alignment, branch target alignment on x86-64
to favor fetch-window boundaries), as placeholders during peephole
optimization (a NOP marks an instruction the rewriter removed but
whose slot must remain for later patching), and as scheduling barriers
in some backends. The unit parameter is accepted for signature
uniformity with other constructors that take operands; it is not
consumed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Construct and return the base LIRInstruction with LIR_NOP opcode.
   A NOP has no operands, so no additional fields need population.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Single 72-byte allocation. Inlinable. The trivial body lets the
optimizer fold the call into a direct base-instruction construction
at most call sites.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe: returns 0 if the base allocation failed. No further state
is initialized.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lir_nop" that takes unit as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc create_lir_instruction with LIR.LIR_NOP
    Return base
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DEBUG PRINTING FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Emits a human-readable representation of a single LIR operand to the
console. Used by debug dumps, compiler-error context, and the LIR
verifier's diagnostic output. The format intentionally mirrors AT&T
assembler syntax — `%rN` for registers, `$N` for immediates, and
`[base + index*scale + displacement]` for memory — so dumped LIR can
be cross-referenced visually with the final assembly output during
backend bring-up.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the operand pointer; print "null" and return 1.
2. Read operand_type at offset 0.
3. For OPERAND_TYPE_REGISTER, read register_id at offset 8 and print
   "%r<id>".
4. For OPERAND_TYPE_IMMEDIATE, read immediate_value at offset 16 and
   print "$<value>".
5. For OPERAND_TYPE_MEMORY, read base, index, scale, and displacement
   from offsets 24, 32, 40, 48. Open with "[", emit "%r<base>" if
   base is non-zero, then " + %r<index>" if index is non-zero (with
   optional "*scale" when scale exceeds 1), then displacement with
   proper sign ("+ N" or "- |N|" when there is a preceding term, or
   the raw value when the expression starts with only a displacement).
   Close with "]".
6. For any unrecognized operand_type, print "unknown_operand" and
   return 0 to signal a malformed operand.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Linear in the number of populated operand fields. Five field reads in
the worst (memory) case, fewer for register and immediate. Used only
for diagnostics, so latency is non-critical; correctness of the
formatting matters more than micro-optimization.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe. Operand-kind discrimination ensures only the fields valid
for the current kind are read — a non-memory operand never causes the
function to read the base/index/scale/displacement slots, which is
defensive against a future layout change.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "print_lir_operand" that takes operand as Integer returns Integer:
    If operand is equal to 0:
        Display "null"
        Return 1
    End If

    Let operand_type be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with operand, 0

    If operand_type is equal to OPERAND_TYPE_REGISTER:
        Let register_id be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with operand, 8
        Display "%r"
        Display register_id
        Return 1
    End If

    If operand_type is equal to OPERAND_TYPE_IMMEDIATE:
        Let immediate_value be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with operand, 16
        Display "$"
        Display immediate_value
        Return 1
    End If

    If operand_type is equal to OPERAND_TYPE_MEMORY:
        Let base be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with operand, 24
        Let index be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with operand, 32
        Let scale be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with operand, 40
        Let displacement be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with operand, 48

        Display "["

        If base is not equal to 0:
            Display "%r"
            Display base
        End If

        If index is not equal to 0:
            If base is not equal to 0:
                Display " + "
            End If
            Display "%r"
            Display index
            If scale is greater than 1:
                Display "*"
                Display scale
            End If
        End If

        If displacement is not equal to 0:
            If base is not equal to 0 or index is not equal to 0:
                If displacement is greater than 0:
                    Display " + "
                Otherwise:
                    Display " - "
                    Set displacement to -displacement
                End If
            End If
            Display displacement
        End If

        Display "]"
        Return 1
    End If

    Display "unknown_operand"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Emits a human-readable representation of one LIR instruction. The
format is "  <opcode_name> <result>, <operand1>, <operand2>,
<operand3>" with operands separated by commas and each rendered via
print_lir_operand. Two-space indentation distinguishes instruction
lines from block labels in the parent function dump. Skipping zeroed
operand slots means a one-operand instruction prints with one operand
and a clean newline, not with trailing commas.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the instruction pointer; print "null instruction" and
   return 0.
2. Read opcode, result, operand1, operand2, and operand3 from offsets
   0, 8, 16, 24, 32.
3. Print two-space indentation, then the opcode name resolved through
   LIR.lir_get_opcode_name, then a separator space.
4. Print result followed by ", " if non-zero.
5. Print operand1 followed by ", " if operand2 is also non-zero (no
   trailing comma when operand1 is the last operand).
6. Print operand2 followed by ", " if operand3 is also non-zero.
7. Print operand3 without a trailing comma.
8. Print an empty line to flush.
9. Return 1 on success.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Five field reads plus up to four operand prints. Diagnostic path only,
so latency is not critical; correctness of the comma placement
matters more.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe at the instruction layer. Each operand print is NULL-safe
itself (print_lir_operand handles the NULL case explicitly), so a
malformed instruction with a NULL operand pointer is rendered as
"null" rather than crashing the diagnostic dump.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "print_lir_instruction" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Display "null instruction"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 0
    Let result be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 8
    Let operand1 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 16
    Let operand2 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 24
    Let operand3 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with instruction, 32

    Note: Print opcode name
    Display "  "
    Let opcode_name be proc lir_get_opcode_name from LIR with opcode
    Display opcode_name
    Display " "

    Note: Print result if present
    If result is not equal to 0:
        proc print_lir_operand with result
        Display ", "
    End If

    Note: Print operand1 if present
    If operand1 is not equal to 0:
        proc print_lir_operand with operand1
        If operand2 is not equal to 0:
            Display ", "
        End If
    End If

    Note: Print operand2 if present
    If operand2 is not equal to 0:
        proc print_lir_operand with operand2
        If operand3 is not equal to 0:
            Display ", "
        End If
    End If

    Note: Print operand3 if present
    If operand3 is not equal to 0:
        proc print_lir_operand with operand3
    End If

    Display ""

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Emits a complete LIR function as a human-readable dump: header banner,
function name, every basic block in declaration order with its label,
and every instruction in each block. Used during backend bring-up,
optimization-pass debugging, and golden-output regression tests. The
banner delimiters make the dump easy to locate inside larger log
output.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the function pointer; print a diagnostic and return 0.
2. Print the opening "========== LIR Function ==========" banner.
3. Read function_name from offset 0; if non-zero, print "Function: "
   followed by the name on its own line.
4. Read the blocks list pointer from offset 32 and the block_count
   from offset 40.
5. If blocks is non-NULL, iterate i from 0 to block_count:
   a. Fetch the i-th block via List.get.
   b. Read block_label from offset 8 of the block and print it on
      its own line followed by ":".
   c. Read the instructions list pointer from offset 16 and the
      instruction count from offset 24.
   d. If instructions is non-NULL, iterate j from 0 to inst_count and
      call print_lir_instruction on each instruction.
6. Print the closing "==================================" banner.
7. Return 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Linear in (block_count × instructions-per-block). Diagnostic path
only; not used in steady-state compilation. Each List.get is a
constant-time array index; print_lir_instruction is itself linear in
operand count.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe at the function pointer, the blocks pointer, the
instructions pointer, and each instruction pointer. A malformed
function with corrupted block-count or instruction-count metadata
will read past its end, but that condition is a verifier-level bug
and not the diagnostic's responsibility to detect.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "print_lir_function" that takes function_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If function_ptr is equal to 0:
        Display "print_lir_function: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Display "========== LIR Function =========="

    Note: Get function name (offset 0 in LIRFunction)
    Let function_name be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with function_ptr, 0
    If function_name is not equal to 0:
        Display "Function: "
        Display function_name
        Display ""
    End If

    Note: Get basic blocks (offset 32 in LIRFunction)
    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with function_ptr, 32
    Note: Get block count (offset 40 in LIRFunction)
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with function_ptr, 40

    If blocks is not equal to 0:
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than block_count:
            Let block be proc list_get from List with blocks, i

            Note: Get block label (offset 8 in LIRBasicBlock)
            Let block_label be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with block, 8
            Display ""
            Display block_label
            Display ":"

            Note: Get instructions in block (offset 16 in LIRBasicBlock)
            Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with block, 16
            Note: Get instruction count (offset 24 in LIRBasicBlock)
            Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with block, 24

            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let j be 0

                While j is less than inst_count:
                    Let instruction be proc list_get from List with instructions, j
                    proc print_lir_instruction with instruction
                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Display "=================================="

    Return 1
End Process
